               <msContents>
                  <textLang mainLang="enm">English. LALME places the language in <placeName
                        key="place_7008143">Herefordshire</placeName> (grid 345 269), LP 7510
                     (3:174). <placeName key="">Leinthall</placeName> (see ‘Provenance’) is six miles
                     south-west of <placeName key="place_7012100">Ludlow</placeName>. </textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_6-item1">
                     <locus from="1ra" to="134ra">Fols. 1<hi rend="superscript">ra</hi>–134<hi
                           rend="superscript">ra</hi></locus>
                     <rubric>Here bygynneþ þe prolog of the seege of Troye in englischs translated
                        after the latyn compiled by Gwydo de Columpnis not word by word</rubric>
                     <incipit>O myghty Mars that with thy sturne light | In armes hast the
                        powwer</incipit>
                     <finalRubric><locus from="133va" to="133va">[fol. 133<hi rend="superscript"
                              >va</hi>]</locus> Thus endeth þe fyfþe booke of þe seege of troye
                        vnder þe correccioun of euery prudent Reeder Quod LIDGATE Monke of þe
                        Burye</finalRubric>
                     <explicit>withdrawe and goo abak | Requerynge hem alle þat is mys to
                        amende</explicit>
                     <colophon>Quod <persName key="person_4617" role="scr">Ion
                              Sch<supplied>row</supplied>sbury</persName></colophon>
                     <author key="person_22158282">John Lydgate</author>
                     <title key="work_2732">The Troy Book</title>
                     <note><bibl>(IMEV 2516)</bibl>, <bibl>ed. Thomas Bergen, EETS ES 97, 103, 106
                           (1906–10)</bibl> , with the envoy and ‘Verba translatoris’ (the actual
                        explicit). Bergen describes our MS at <bibl>EETS ES 126 (1935) 36–8.</bibl>
                        <locus from="134rb" to="134v">Fol. 134<hi rend="superscript"
                           >rb-v</hi></locus> originally blank. This copy lacks Prol.210–1.49 on a
                        lost leaf following <locus from="1r" to="1v">fol. 1</locus> (the original
                           2<hi rend="superscript">o</hi> folio should have been a version of 1.50
                        ‘Fordymmed eke the lettris aureat’). The scribe has left blanks marked with
                        crosses for missing lines; cf. <locus from="43ra" to="43ra">fol. 43<hi
                              rend="superscript">ra</hi></locus>, with the informal <term
                           type="script">anglicana</term> note ‘caret versus’ <date
                           calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="1475" notAfter="1500">(s. xv ex.)</date>.
                        This feature is genetic, shared with three closely related books: <bibl
                           type="MS">Gloucester Cathedral MS 5;</bibl>
                        <bibl type="MS">Manchester, John Rylands University Library, MS Eng.
                           1;</bibl> and <bibl type="MS">BodL, MS Digby 230.</bibl>
                     </note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="2" xml:id="St_Johns_College_MS_6-item2">
                     <locus from="134ra" to="134ra">Fol. 134<hi rend="superscript">ra</hi></locus>
                     <incipit>Pees makeþ plente | Plente makyþ pryde</incipit>
                     <note><bibl>IMEV 2742</bibl>, written in rubricator’s red; <bibl>ed. Bergen,
                           26</bibl>, from the related <bibl type="MS">Digby 230</bibl>, where it
                        appears in the same position and format.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
